Produce comprehensive team meeting minutes using every section below. Extract ALL relevant information from the transcript. If a topic was not discussed, write "Not discussed in this meeting."

## Title
[Specific, descriptive title — 3 to 10 words. NOT "Team Meeting" or "Weekly Sync" — name the actual topics covered.]

## Summary
[4-6 sentences: meeting purpose, key decisions made, critical blockers raised, financial highlights, and any urgent items. This should give someone who missed the meeting a complete picture in 30 seconds.]

## Detailed Notes
[A comprehensive narrative write-up of the team meeting (~600–1500 words — longer than other meeting types because team meetings cover more ground). Walk through the meeting roughly in the order topics came up: how the meeting opened, how each agenda item was introduced, how the conversation developed, what pushback or concerns were raised, and how each topic resolved. Capture the reasoning, trade-offs, alternatives considered, and open questions behind each discussion — not just the conclusions. Attribute key points, positions, and commitments to named participants. Include concrete details (numbers, dates, systems, incidents, teams, customers). Use ## / ### subheadings, paragraphs, and bullets for readability. Do not duplicate the structured sections below verbatim — weave the narrative around them. This is the deep record absent team members will rely on. Only include information actually present in the transcript.]

## Prior Action Items Review
[Were any action items from previous meetings discussed? For each, note: the original item, who owned it, and the status update given (completed / in progress / blocked / not started / dropped). If prior items were not reviewed, write "Not reviewed in this meeting."]

## Decisions Made
[THE MOST IMPORTANT SECTION. For each decision, capture ALL of the following:]
- **Decision**: [Clear statement of what was decided]
- **Rationale**: [Why this was decided — the reasoning]
- **Options considered**: [What alternatives were discussed and rejected]
- **Approved by**: [Who made or approved the decision]
- **Scope/constraints**: [Any limitations, conditions, or caveats]

[If no formal decisions were made, note any near-decisions or items that need a decision at the next meeting.]

## Financial Review
[Capture ALL financial and budget discussions. If finance was not discussed, write "Not discussed."]

### Cloud Spend & Budget
[Current vs. budgeted spend, variances, trends, cost anomalies. Break down by provider/service if discussed:]
- AWS spend: [actuals vs. forecast, notable services driving cost]
- NetApp spend: [licensing, capacity, usage trends]
- Other vendor spend: [tools, SaaS, contractor costs]

### Cost Optimization
[Savings identified, actions taken, ROI of previous optimization efforts, upcoming commitment renewals or purchases]

### Business/P&L Impact
[How team costs relate to revenue, margin targets, or budget constraints. Any financial decisions or approvals needed.]

## Blockers, Risks & Escalations
[For EACH blocker or risk, capture: what it is, who is impacted, severity, who owns resolution, escalation path if unresolved, and current status.]

### Operational Blockers
[System outages, access problems, tooling failures, deployment issues, on-call burden, incident response gaps, environment issues. Include impact assessment.]

### Organizational Blockers
[Unclear ownership, cross-team dependencies, approval bottlenecks, communication gaps, staffing shortages, unclear priorities, process friction. Note which team or person the dependency is on.]

### Infrastructure / Physical Blockers
[Hardware, network, data center, capacity constraints, connectivity issues, equipment needs.]

### Strategic / Roadmap Blockers
[Product direction uncertainty, feature prioritization conflicts, technical debt preventing progress, architecture decisions pending, migration timeline risks, vendor decisions needed.]

### Cross-Team Dependencies
[For each dependency on another team:]
- What: [what is needed]
- From: [which team]
- Committed date: [when they promised]
- Status: [on track / at risk / slipping]
- Escalation: [who to escalate to if slipping]

## Strategic & Roadmap Updates
[Capture all strategy and direction discussions:]
- OKR / goal progress updates
- Roadmap changes or reprioritization
- Leadership direction communicated
- Market/competitive context shared
- Build vs. buy discussions
- Migration or platform strategy updates

## Technology Decisions & Architecture
[Capture all technical discussions:]
- Architecture decisions made (ADR-worthy items)
- Technology choices or evaluations
- Technical debt discussions and prioritization
- Platform/tooling changes
- Security and compliance discussions
- Innovation and experimentation updates

## Service & Platform Feedback

### AWS Services
[Feedback, issues, or discussions about AWS services (EC2, S3, Lambda, EKS, SageMaker, Bedrock, Control Tower, Security Hub, IAM, CloudFormation, etc.). Include: performance, reliability, cost, feature gaps, and migration experiences.]

### NetApp Services
[Feedback on ONTAP, Cloud Volumes, StorageGRID, BlueXP, Astra, FSx for NetApp ONTAP, etc.]

### Other Services & Tools
[Jira, Confluence, Slack, GitHub, CI/CD, monitoring, internal platforms, etc.]

## Customer & Business Impact
[What was discussed about customers, SLAs, and business outcomes:]
- Recent incidents and their customer impact
- SLA performance and trends
- Customer-reported issues escalated to the team
- Upcoming customer commitments affecting the team
- Feedback from customer-facing teams

## Resource & Capacity
[Staffing, workload, and hiring discussions:]
- Current headcount vs. needs
- Hiring pipeline updates (open reqs, interviews, start dates)
- Skill gaps identified
- Workload distribution concerns (overloaded individuals or areas)
- Upcoming capacity changes (PTO, departures, rotations, training)
- Contractor/vendor resource needs

## Team Health & Morale
[Signals about how the team is doing — capture these even if discussed informally:]
- Wins and recognition shared (celebrate accomplishments explicitly)
- Morale observations (energy level, engagement in discussion)
- Burnout or stress signals (late nights, incident fatigue, complaints about workload)
- Process improvement suggestions from the team
- Cultural or collaboration observations
- Work-life balance discussions

## Announcements & Information Shared
[Important updates communicated during the meeting:]
- Company/org announcements relayed
- Policy or process changes
- Upcoming events, deadlines, or milestones
- Training opportunities or resources shared
- Personnel changes announced

## Parking Lot
[Topics raised but deferred to a future meeting. For each: what the topic is and when it should be revisited.]

